<h1>Ketamine for Alcohol Withdrawal 2026</h1>
<p class="hub-crumb" style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:0.9em;background:#f0f4ff;border-left:4px solid #3b6cf8;padding:8px 14px;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;margin:14px 0;">Part of the <a href="icu-pharmacology-hub-2026.html"><strong>ICU Pharmacology Hub</strong></a> &mdash; browse every related guide in one place.</p>
<!-- MEDICAL DISCLAIMER — required for health/clinical content -->
<p style="font-size:0.85em;color:#888;font-style:italic;border-left:3px solid #e5e7eb;padding-left:10px;margin:8px 0 16px;">
  <strong>Medical Disclaimer:</strong> This article is general educational information for licensed clinicians and students, not medical advice or a substitute for your institution's protocols or a provider's orders. Always follow your facility's policies and a provider's orders.
</p>
<!-- END MEDICAL DISCLAIMER -->
<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">When a patient in severe alcohol withdrawal is burning through escalating benzodiazepine doses and still agitated, tremulous, and tachycardic, the team starts looking for a partner drug that works by a different mechanism. Increasingly that partner is a low-dose ketamine infusion. Used as an adjunct &mdash; not a replacement &mdash; ketamine targets the exact receptor system that makes late withdrawal so benzodiazepine-resistant.</p>
<div class="hero-note">
<strong>The core idea:</strong> Alcohol withdrawal is a two-receptor problem. Chronic alcohol suppresses excitatory NMDA glutamate receptors and enhances inhibitory GABA. Stop drinking and the brain is left with a flood of up-regulated, over-active NMDA receptors that benzodiazepines (which work on GABA) can't touch. Ketamine is an NMDA-receptor antagonist &mdash; it works on the arm of the problem benzos miss.
</div>

<h2>Why benzodiazepines alone hit a ceiling</h2>
<p>Benzodiazepines are still first-line for alcohol withdrawal because they restore GABA-mediated inhibition and prevent seizures. But in the sickest patients &mdash; those heading into delirium tremens &mdash; the driving pathology shifts toward glutamate excess at NMDA receptors. You can keep climbing the benzo dose (and many protocols do, reaching alarming cumulative amounts), but you're pushing on the GABA side of a problem that has become largely glutamatergic. That's when you see "benzodiazepine-resistant" withdrawal: huge doses, deepening sedation, and still-present autonomic storm. Adding an NMDA antagonist addresses the untreated half of the receptor imbalance.</p>

<h2>Where ketamine fits in the escalation ladder</h2>
<p>Ketamine is an adjunct, layered on when benzodiazepines alone aren't controlling symptoms and the team wants to avoid or limit intubation. A typical severe-withdrawal escalation looks like this:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Step</th><th>Agent</th><th>Mechanism</th></tr>
<tr><td>First-line</td><td>Benzodiazepines (symptom-triggered / CIWA)</td><td>Enhance GABA</td></tr>
<tr><td>Add for refractory</td><td><a href="phenobarbital-guide-icu-nurses-2026.html">Phenobarbital</a></td><td>GABA + some glutamate effect</td></tr>
<tr><td>Add for benzo-resistant</td><td><strong>Ketamine infusion (adjunct)</strong></td><td>NMDA-receptor antagonism</td></tr>
<tr><td>Rescue / airway lost</td><td>Propofol / dexmedetomidine, intubation</td><td>GABA / alpha-2</td></tr>
</table>
<p>The appeal of adding ketamine before propofol is that ketamine is <em>benzodiazepine-sparing</em> and generally preserves respiratory drive and airway reflexes. Getting withdrawal under control without intubating a patient is a meaningful win &mdash; it avoids ventilator days, sedation cascades, and delirium.</p>

<h2>Dosing you'll see at the bedside</h2>
<p>For alcohol withdrawal, ketamine is used at low, sub-anesthetic (analgesic/adjunct) doses &mdash; far below procedural-sedation or induction doses. Institutions vary, but low continuous infusions in the range of roughly 0.1&ndash;0.5 mg/kg/hr are common, sometimes with a small loading dose, titrated to symptom control and sedation goals. This is a protocol- and pharmacist-driven decision; always run your unit's specific order set. The point to internalize as a nurse is that this is a <em>low-dose adjunct</em> infusion, not the dissociative dose used for intubation &mdash; if someone writes for an induction-range dose "for withdrawal," question it.</p>
<div class="warning">
<strong>This is not the same as the general ketamine playbook.</strong> Dissociation, emergence phenomena, and hemodynamic surge are dose-dependent and much more prominent at sedation/induction doses. See our <a href="ketamine-guide-icu-nurses-2026.html">full ICU ketamine guide</a> for the drug's complete profile. In withdrawal you're deliberately staying in the low-dose lane to get NMDA blockade without those effects.</p>
</div>

<h2>What to monitor</h2>
<p>Ketamine is a sympathomimetic &mdash; it raises heart rate and blood pressure &mdash; which matters in a population already tachycardic and hypertensive from withdrawal. Watch for:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Monitor</th><th>Why</th></tr>
<tr><td>Heart rate &amp; blood pressure</td><td>Ketamine adds sympathetic tone on top of withdrawal's; watch for excessive tachycardia/hypertension</td></tr>
<tr><td>Sedation / agitation (RASS)</td><td>Titrate to a calm, arousable target; the goal is control, not deep sedation</td></tr>
<tr><td>Dissociation / emergence reactions</td><td>More likely if the dose creeps up; vivid dreams, agitation on wake-up</td></tr>
<tr><td>Respiratory drive &amp; airway</td><td>Usually preserved, but stacking with high-dose benzos/phenobarbital can still depress it</td></tr>
<tr><td>Total benzodiazepine requirement</td><td>The success metric &mdash; a falling benzo requirement shows the adjunct is working</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Don't forget the withdrawal fundamentals ketamine doesn't fix: aggressive <a href="thiamine-guide-icu-nurses-2026.html">thiamine</a> before glucose to prevent Wernicke, electrolyte repletion (magnesium, potassium, phosphate), and seizure vigilance. Ketamine calms the receptor storm; it doesn't replace banana bags done right or CIWA-driven benzo dosing.</p>

<h2>Contraindications and cautions</h2>
<p>Be cautious in patients where a further catecholamine surge is dangerous &mdash; poorly controlled hypertension, active coronary ischemia, or known severe cardiac disease. Ketamine can raise intracranial and intraocular pressure, so consider the neuro picture. And remember the practical reality: many withdrawal patients have co-ingestions and unknown histories, so the team weighs ketamine's sympathetic effects against the alternative of runaway benzodiazepine escalation and intubation.</p>
<div class="callout">
<strong>Bottom line:</strong> Ketamine earns its place in severe, benzodiazepine-resistant alcohol withdrawal because it treats the NMDA/glutamate half of the problem that benzos can't reach. Used as a low-dose, benzo-sparing adjunct, it can help control the autonomic storm and keep a patient off the ventilator &mdash; while you monitor the added sympathetic load and keep the withdrawal basics (thiamine, electrolytes, seizure prophylaxis) locked in.
</div>

<p>This is clinical education for licensed nurses, not a protocol or medical advice &mdash; always follow your institution's order sets and pharmacist guidance. Related reading: our <a href="ketamine-guide-icu-nurses-2026.html">ICU ketamine guide</a>, <a href="lorazepam-ativan-guide-icu-nurses-2026.html">lorazepam</a>, <a href="phenobarbital-guide-icu-nurses-2026.html">phenobarbital</a>, and <a href="thiamine-guide-icu-nurses-2026.html">thiamine</a>.</p>

